   {:e #blake3 "c8a5a10e3d1b02947b1a0a799968461f3f06ddacd9337d94d0e7625dd6a5aa3b" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :recon/trace-1f1e46e982fb0e23; UAQ INSIGHT 17: HEBBIAN-BAYESIAN DYNAMICS — PRECISE FORMULAS. The connection lifecycle requires three concrete computations: \n\nHEBBIAN CO-ACTIVATION BOOST: When entities A and B are activated in the same context, their connection gets boost = proximity_weight * activation_strength. Proximity weights: same_command = 1.0 (agent's action directly references both), same_session = 0.5 (both activated within one session but different commands), adjacent_session = 0.25 (activated in consecutive sessions). Accumulation: hebbian_boost += boost. Decay: hebbian_boost *= 0.5 per session (half-life). This is already the ATT-2 Hebbian model, now generalized to all connection types.\n\nBAYESIAN POSTERIOR CONFIDENCE: When a connection prediction is tested (agent confirms or rejects a proposed edge), update confidence: posterior = (prior * likelihood) / evidence. In practice: confidence = confirmed_count / (confirmed_count + rejected_count + smoothing). Smoothing = 2.0 (Laplace prior, prevents extreme confidence from small samples). After 8 confirmations and 2 rejections with smoothing=2: confidence = 10/14 = 0.71. This is already the hypothesis ledger's calibration model, now generalized.\n\nTEMPORAL DECAY: Connections not activated decay geometrically: confidence *= decay_rate^sessions_since_last_activation. decay_rate = 0.9. After 5 sessions without activation: 0.9^5 = 0.59 of original confidence. After 10: 0.9^10 = 0.35. After 20: 0.9^20 = 0.12. Entity-change signal: if the SOURCE or TARGET entity receives new datoms, all connections FROM/TO that entity get accelerated decay (decay_rate = 0.7 instead of 0.9) until re-verified.\n\nCOMBINED: effective_weight = bayesian_confidence * temporal_decay * (1 + hebbian_boost). The hebbian_boost is additive (can exceed 1.0 for strongly co-activated connections), while confidence and decay are multiplicative gates. This is the learned_weight in the attention schema.\n\nSPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-029, ADR-FOUNDATION-024. FILE: These formulas belong in a new connection_dynamics() function, likely in methodology.rs or a new connections.rs module.; UAQ INSIGHT 18: WITNESS SUGGESTION IN STATUS OUTPUT — THE CONCRETE UX. When braid status runs and unwitnessed INVs exist with name-matchable tests (scan_source already identifies these), the status output should include a suggested witness pairing as a scored context block. FORMAT: 'suggest: test_merge_commutativity → INV-MERGE-001 (alpha=0.34) — confirm: braid witness confirm INV-MERGE-001 test_merge_commutativity'. This is a ContextBlock with: kind=ObservationKind::WitnessSuggestion (future, use ContextBlock for now), impact = F(S) improvement from one more witnessed INV = 1/total_unwitnessed (normalized), cost = tokens for the suggestion line (~15 tokens), alpha = impact/cost. The agent confirms with ONE COMMAND: braid witness confirm. The witness count goes up. F(S) goes up. The acquisition function calibrates from the confirmation. Next session, better pairings proposed. IMPLEMENTATION: In UAQ-3 (context block scoring), add a new block source: unwitnessed_inv_suggestions(). This function: (1) Gets unwitnessed INVs from witness_gaps(store). (2) For each, searches test function names in trace data for keyword overlap with the INV name/falsification. (3) Ranks by match quality. (4) Returns top-1 as a ContextBlock with AcquisitionScore. (5) The block competes with all other blocks for budget. If it survives, the agent sees the suggestion. If budget cuts it, the INV stays unwitnessed until alpha increases (maybe next session when other blocks have decayed via novelty). IMPLEMENTATION COST: ~100 LOC in context.rs + ~20 LOC for braid witness confirm subcommand. SPEC: INV-WITNESS-011, ADR-FOUNDATION-025, ADR-FOUNDATION-028.; UAQ INSIGHT 19: ATT-0 SCHEMA REINTERPRETATION. The six :attention/* attributes already in Layer 2 schema (added in ATT-0/ATT-1 earlier this session) are not attention-specific. They are CONNECTION LIFECYCLE attributes. The NAMES should be understood as: :attention/block-label → connection kind identifier (what type of edge this is). :attention/presentation-count → activation count (how many times this connection was exercised). :attention/last-presented → last activation timestamp (when was this connection most recently confirmed/used). :attention/hebbian-boost → Hebbian co-activation accumulator (strengthening from correlated use). :attention/learned-weight → Bayesian posterior confidence * temporal decay (the effective connection weight). :attention/calibration-count → number of Bayesian updates (how much evidence informs the confidence). For Phase D: these attributes are applied to ContextBlock entities (attention scoring) and WitnessPairing entities (witness suggestion scoring). For Phase E: they extend to TraceLink entities, Hypothesis entities, and cross-project TransferEdge entities. NO SCHEMA CHANGE NEEDED — the attributes are already defined. Only the INTERPRETATION changes. The AcquisitionScore computation reads these attributes. The feedback loop writes them. The decay function updates them. SPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-029.; Session entity: :recon/trace-2d4b21c512133605; Session entity: :task/t-77d456ed; UAQ INSIGHT 15: WITNESS PAIRING IS A UAQ INSTANCE. The witness gap (32/272 = 12% coverage) is not a special problem requiring a special solution. It is ANOTHER instance of the universal acquisition function. \n\nA proposed witness pairing is a CONTEXT BLOCK: 'Test test_merge_commutativity likely witnesses INV-MERGE-001 because both reference set-union ordering.' This block has: impact = F(S) improvement from confirming the pairing (one more witnessed INV). cost = agent attention tokens to review and confirm/reject. alpha = impact / cost.\n\nThe hypothesis ledger tracks whether the agent CONFIRMED the pairing. Confirmed = hypothesis correct (the test does witness the INV). Rejected = hypothesis wrong (false positive). The acquisition function learns which test-INV similarity signals predict correct pairings.\n\nTHIS MEANS: the UAQ doesn't just unify five recommendation systems. It unifies ALL information-selection problems in the system. Witness pairing, task routing, context projection, ceremony adaptation, harvest timing — they're all 'which information should I present to maximize ΔF(S) per token?'\n\nThe witness gap resolves itself over time: each session, the acquisition function proposes the highest-alpha witness pairings. The agent confirms or rejects. The calibration improves. After 10 sessions, most high-confidence pairings are confirmed and F(S) reflects real coverage.\n\nThis is the observation-projection duality at the verification layer: tests are observations of invariant behavior. Witnesses are projections of those observations onto the spec graph. The acquisition function optimizes the projection.\n\nSPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-025, ADR-FOUNDATION-028, INV-WITNESS-011.; Session entity: :recon/trace-9a904de2e80a9abe; Session entity: :task/t-e7d3b693; WITNESS ARCHITECTURE DEEP ANALYSIS: THE SEMANTIC PAIRING PROBLEM. \n\nTHE GAP: 272 invariants exist. 1,386 tests exist. 32 witnesses exist. The tests DO test the invariants — but the system can't PROVE which test covers which invariant.\n\nWHY: The witness system (INV-WITNESS-001..011) requires EXPLICIT pairing: a Falsification-Bound Witness (FBW) links one INV entity to one test function with a verification depth. The trace scanner finds 464 spec-entity references across 84 source files (90% coverage). But references in doc comments (// INV-STORE-001: ...) are DOCUMENTATION, not test evidence. promote_tests_to_l2 only handles Kani proofs and Stateright models with HARDCODED binding tables.\n\nTHE REAL PROBLEM: This is an OBSERVATION-PROJECTION DUALITY gap at the verification layer. The tests are OBSERVATIONS of invariant behavior. The witnesses are PROJECTIONS of those observations onto the spec graph. The gap between 1,386 tests and 32 witnesses is the round-trip error of the verification projection.\n\nTHREE APPROACHES TO CLOSE THE GAP:\n\nAPPROACH A — NAME-BASED MATCHING (simple, partial): Test functions that contain an INV ID in their name or body are automatically paired. Example: test_merge_is_commutative contains 'INV-MERGE-001' in a comment → auto-witness. Coverage: maybe 10-20% of tests name their INV explicitly. Effort: extend scan_source to extract test-level INV refs (it already extracts module-level ones).\n\nAPPROACH B — SEMANTIC MATCHING (medium, good coverage): For each INV, extract the falsification condition (a natural language description of what would violate it). For each test, extract the assertion pattern (what the test actually checks). Use string similarity / keyword overlap to SUGGEST pairings. Present to the agent for confirmation. Coverage: 40-60% with good false-positive rate. Effort: moderate — bag-of-words similarity is ~50 LOC.\n\nAPPROACH C — THE ACQUISITION FUNCTION SOLUTION (deep, correct): A witness pairing IS a recommendation. The system recommends 'test T likely witnesses INV I.' The recommendation has an expected_delta_fs (how much F(S) improves if the pairing is confirmed), a cost (agent attention tokens to review the pairing), and an alpha. The hypothesis ledger tracks which recommended pairings the agent confirmed vs rejected. Over time, the system learns which test patterns correspond to which invariant patterns. THIS IS UAQ APPLIED TO WITNESS COVERAGE. The witness gap isn't a special problem — it's another instance of the universal acquisition function selecting the highest-value information to present. The 'information' is a proposed witness pairing. The 'cost' is the review overhead. The 'alpha' is the expected F(S) improvement from confirmed coverage.\n\nRECOMMENDATION: Approach A first (immediate, low effort, closes ~20% of gap). Then Approach C as part of UAQ (the correct general solution). Approach B is superseded by C.\n\nSPEC: INV-WITNESS-011 (every current-stage INV must have L2+), ADR-FOUNDATION-025 (UAQ).; Session entity: :recon/trace-b2bafe2cfac62140; UAQ INSIGHT 16: THE KNOWLEDGE GRAPH IS THE KNOWLEDGE. Knowledge is not entities or datoms — it is the CONNECTIONS between them. An isolated INV is opinion. An INV connected to a test (witness) connected to source (trace) connected to a task (routing) connected to an outcome (hypothesis) IS knowledge. F(S) measures connection graph density. Every metric braid computes is a measurement of connection quality. THE CONNECTION LIFECYCLE: (1) BIRTH — proposed by trace scanner, acquisition function, or harvest. Low confidence. (2) ACTIVATION — agent interacts (follows recommendation, confirms witness, commits observation). Evidence accumulates. (3) STRENGTHENING (Hebbian) — co-activated connections strengthen. Same-command=1.0, same-session=0.5, adjacent-session=0.25. Fire together wire together. (4) CALIBRATION (Bayesian) — hypothesis ledger updates posterior confidence from prediction outcomes. 10 activations with 8 confirmations → confidence 0.8. (5) DECAY — unused connections weaken. 0.9^sessions temporal decay. Source entity changes → staleness signal → faster decay until re-verified. (6) DEATH — sustained zero confidence. Remains in store (C1 append-only) but contributes nothing. Resurrectable if new evidence appears. THREE FORCES: Hebbian growth (fast/per-session), Bayesian calibration (medium/per-phase), Structural discovery (slow/per-domain, Phase E). DEEPEST INSIGHT: The six ATT-0 schema attributes are not for context blocks — they are CONNECTION LIFECYCLE attributes. presentation-count=activation count, last-presented=last activation, hebbian-boost=co-activation accumulator, learned-weight=Bayesian posterior, calibration-count=update count, block-label=connection kind. EVERY connection type (witness, trace, hypothesis, attention) should carry these six attributes. One schema. One lifecycle. One learning dynamic. SPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-025, ADR-FOUNDATION-028, ADR-FOUNDATION-024.; Session entity: :recon/trace-2c3dfc484fb6ccef; Session entity: :task/t-43517ffc; Session entity: :recon/trace-a5bd05d0c95da65e; Session entity: :recon/trace-1764626683301c0e; Session entity: :recon/trace-44c86a9576fe98cd; Session entity: :task/t-9887a59d\nSession entity: :task/t-f4d8c263; Session entity: :task/t-89f8062b; Connection Lifecycle as Universal Schema — the six attention attributes are connection dynamics, not block metadata" :op :assert}
